# ğŸ³ Docker Cheatsheet for MkDocs Projects

This guide covers essential Docker commands for building, troubleshooting, and serving your MkDocs site.

---

## ğŸ“¦ Build Docker Image

Build the image from your Dockerfile (assumes it's in the root directory):

```bash
docker build -t mkdocs-site .
```

- `-t mkdocs-site`: Tags the image for easy reference
- `.`: Builds from current directory

---

## ğŸš€ Serve MkDocs Site with Live Reload

Run the container and serve your site with live reload enabled:

```bash
docker run --rm -p 8000:8000 -v "$PWD":/app mkdocs-site mkdocs serve --dev-addr=0.0.0.0:8000 --livereload
```

- `--rm`: Removes container after exit  
- `-p 8000:8000`: Maps container port to host  
- `-v "$PWD":/app`: Mounts current directory into container  
- `--livereload`: Enables automatic browser refresh on file changes  

Access your site at: [http://localhost:8000](http://localhost:8000)

---

## ğŸ” Troubleshooting Tips

### ğŸ› ï¸ Rebuild Image (if dependencies change)

```bash
docker build --no-cache -t mkdocs-site .
```

### ğŸ§¼ Remove Dangling Images

```bash
docker image prune
```

### ğŸ“‹ List Running Containers

```bash
docker ps
```

### ğŸ§¯ Stop a Running Container

```bash
docker stop <container_id>
```

### ğŸ§³ Enter a Running Container (for debugging)

```bash
docker exec -it <container_id> /bin/sh
```

---

## ğŸ“ Volume Mounting Notes

Ensure your project folder contains:
- `mkdocs.yml`
- `docs/` directory with markdown files

Changes to these files will trigger live reload if mounted correctly.

---

## ğŸ§ª Test Static Build

Generate the static site without serving:

```bash
docker run --rm -v "$PWD":/app mkdocs-site mkdocs build
```

Output will be in the `site/` folder.

---

## ğŸ§¼ Clean Up Docker System (Optional)

```bash
docker system prune -a
```

âš ï¸ This removes all unused containers, images, and networks.

---

## ğŸ“Œ Notes

- Always rebuild the image if you change dependencies in `requirements.txt` or the Dockerfile.
- For multi-machine setups, commit your `Dockerfile` and rebuild locally, or push the image to a registry.
